{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-template-js","path":"/blog/htmlbasics/","webpackCompilationHash":"12e47ffb49087e82ee32","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>In this blog, I would like to cover the absolute basics of building a webpage from scratch. You will be introduced to elements such as head, body,div, etc and all other necessary terms that help you build a webpage from scratch. Another important topic that we will discuss is the structure of the HTML page. </p>\n<p>First things first:</p>\n<h2>What is HTML?</h2>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">“Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) is the standard markup language \nfor documents designed to be displayed in a web browser. \nIt can be assisted by technologies such as Cascading Style Sheets(CSS) \nand scripting languages such as JavaScript (JS).” </code></pre></div>\n<div style=\"float: right\"> -The holy grail of students: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">Wikipedia</a> </div>\n<br/>\n<h2>Structure of your webpage:</h2>\n<Insert the image>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 67.2072072072072%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"HTML\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/34e8a/html_structure.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/d4214/html_structure.png 150w,\n/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/135ae/html_structure.png 300w,\n/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/34e8a/html_structure.png 600w,\n/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/fea0e/html_structure.png 900w,\n/static/8a94535bf5a4c4f86ceebe6e78e3cdb2/dbb75/html_structure.png 1110w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n<em>As every Indian professor says after drawing something: \"Sorry I don’t know how to draw\"</em></p>\n<p>As described in the above image, the whole structure of a webpage is divided into 2 parts: Head and Body. The whole section of your code is enclosed into the HTML tag and the file is saved with an extension of .html</p>\n<hr/>\n<p>To define any section on a webpage we enclose it inside a tag.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.1764705882353%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"HTML Element\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/34e8a/html_element.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/d4214/html_element.png 150w,\n/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/135ae/html_element.png 300w,\n/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/34e8a/html_element.png 600w,\n/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/fea0e/html_element.png 900w,\n/static/d484a140f30d4b7351053e5bca2c7824/89b07/html_element.png 1020w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>The main parts of our element are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The opening tag</strong>: This consists of the name of the element (in this case, p), wrapped in opening and closing angle brackets. This states where the element begins or starts to take effect — in this case where the start of the paragraph is.</li>\n<li><strong>The closing tag</strong>: This is the same as the opening tag, except that it includes a forward slash before the element name. This states where the element ends — in this case where the end of the paragraph is. Failing to include a closing tag is a common beginner error and can lead to strange results.</li>\n<li><strong>The content</strong>: This is the content of the element, which in this case is just text.</li>\n<li><strong>The element</strong>: The opening tag plus the closing tag plus the content equals the element.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr/>\n<p>One interesting point to note here is using nested elements. Just like any other programming language, you can nest elements inside one another.</p>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;p&gt; The parent tag &lt;b&gt; The Nested tag &lt;/b&gt; !! &lt;/p&gt;</code> </p>\n<p><em>Produces the output:</em> <p> The parent tag <b> The Nested tag </b> !! </p></p>\n<h2>Most used tags</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;p&gt;</code> - To start a paragraph</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;div&gt;</code> - To start any section</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;img src=””&gt;</code> - To insert an image</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;a href=””&gt;</code> - To insert any link</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;br/&gt;</code> - Line break</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;hr/&gt;</code> - Line break witha visible horizontal line</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Some commonly tags used for formatting the content:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;b&gt;</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">&lt;strong&gt;</code> - Bold Case</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;i&gt;</code> - italics</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;em&gt;</code> - Emphasized </li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;del&gt;</code> - deleted text</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;sub&gt;</code> - subscript text</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;sup&gt;</code> - superscript text</li>\n</ul>\n<iframe height=\"265\" style=\"width: 100%;\" scrolling=\"no\" title=\"Basic HTML\" src=\"https://codepen.io/wizard-1910/embed/dyyMqNb?height=265&theme-id=dark&default-tab=html,result\" frameborder=\"no\" allowtransparency=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"true\">\n  See the Pen <a href='https://codepen.io/wizard-1910/pen/dyyMqNb'>Basic HTML</a> by Aman Dave\n  (<a href='https://codepen.io/wizard-1910'>@wizard-1910</a>) on <a href='https://codepen.io'>CodePen</a>.\n</iframe>\n<hr/>\n<br/>\n<p>Now let’s look at something that will make this above things more colorful.</p>\n<h2>What is CSS?</h2>\n<p>CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is what makes web pages look good and presentable. It’s an essential part of modern web development and a must-have skill for any web designer and developer. </p>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">&lt;h1 style=&quot;color: red&quot;&gt; Hello world! &lt;/h1&gt;</code></p>\n<p><em>Produces Output:</em> <h1 style=\"color: red\"> Hello world! </h1> </p>\n<hr/>\n<h2>Selecting particular element</h2>\n<p>We have two possible ways of doing it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Class:</strong> We can select a particular HTML element by giving it a particular class. Once we have associated a given element with a class, we can define as many styling options we want to that class. </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>div</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">class</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">'</span>heading<span class=\"token punctuation\">'</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>  \n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>h1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span> This is heading <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>h1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>  \n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token selector\">.container</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>  \n<span class=\"token property\">font-size</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> 30px<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>  \n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p><em>Output:</em></p>\n<div style=\"font-size: 30px\">  \n<h1> This is heading </h1>  \n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Id:</strong> Very similar to the class we saw above, the only difference being id can be used to one particular element whereas we can have many-to-many relation between elements and classes.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>  \n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>p</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">id</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">'</span>para1<span class=\"token punctuation\">'</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span> This is a paragraph <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>  \n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token selector\">#para1</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>  \n<span class=\"token property\">color</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> green<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>  \n<span class=\"token property\">font-size</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> 24px<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>  \n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p><em>Output:</em> </p>\n<div>  \n<p style=\"font-size:24px; color:green\"> This is a paragraph </p>  \n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<br/>\n<hr/>\n<h2>Hands-On Practice</h2>\n<p>If you enjoyed the above article and would like to build something from scratch, I have something for you.</p>\n<h4>Basic Trip-Management Website</h4>\n<p>I have created a template that will help you get going with HTML and CSS, also Javascript.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54.166666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Home\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/34e8a/home.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/d4214/home.png 150w,\n/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/135ae/home.png 300w,\n/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/34e8a/home.png 600w,\n/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/fea0e/home.png 900w,\n/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/6ff5e/home.png 1200w,\n/static/f427955d59e4f48e34fbdf0b9128a766/a987b/home.png 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 600px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54.166666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Transport\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/34e8a/transport.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/d4214/transport.png 150w,\n/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/135ae/transport.png 300w,\n/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/34e8a/transport.png 600w,\n/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/fea0e/transport.png 900w,\n/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/6ff5e/transport.png 1200w,\n/static/5cc41f487cea5291003f6ff00bc0f3b6/a987b/transport.png 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>GitHub Repository: <a href=\"https://github.com/wizArD-1910/html_basic\">wizArD-1910/html_basics</a></p>\n<p>And the live website can be visited at: <a href=\"https://www.amandave.dev/html_basic/\">HTML_BASICS</a>  \n<em>[Username: user@gmail.com || Password: pass]</em></p>\n<p>Go to the above link, clone it on your computer. Open the <code class=\"language-text\">index.html</code> to see the website.\nI have added a lot of comments in the code to help you understand which section is used for what. For CSS, I have used <a href=\"https://getbootstrap.com\">Bootstrap</a>. It helps in creating beautiful and responsive components very easily. </p>\n<p>For those who like some challenges, I have left an exercise for you to complete. It contains adding Javascript code to one of the pages so as to display inputs given by users. I have already done it once for you, you have to figure it out for other elements. If you feel you have solved the issue, feel free to fork the repository, send a PR. I will go through it and accept if the underlying issue is fixed.</p>","frontmatter":{"date":"October 16, 2019","title":"Getting started with HTML"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/blog/htmlbasics/"}}}